{
    "assignee": null,
    "body": "With node-minecraft-protocol embracing ES6 (https://github.com/PrismarineJS/node-minecraft-protocol/pull/322 et. al.), I think it is worth considering updating the variable declarations to use the new block-scoped `let` and `const` keywords, instead of the function-scoped `var`. Current status:\r\n\r\n```\r\nnode-minecraft-protocol $ grep -r 'var ' src/|wc -l\r\n     175\r\nnode-minecraft-protocol $ grep -r 'let ' src/|wc -l\r\n       3\r\nnode-minecraft-protocol $ grep -r 'const ' src/|wc -l\r\n       0\r\n```\r\n\r\nMany of the `var`s could be updated to `const`s (if assigned only once), and the others to `let`s. `let` avoids some of the pitfalls of `var`'s scoping rules.\r\n\r\nNew code can use let/const, but it feels odd to have a mix of let/const/var, so a comprehensive conversion could make sense. Should be a fairly easy change to make, but results in a large diff and will cause merge conflicts so I've put it off for now.",
